UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# CSS Flexbox Layout — The Complete Guide\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nBefore Flexbox, centering a div was a running joke among developers. Positioning elements side-by-side required floats, clearfixes, and prayers. Flexbox changed everything.\n\n**Flexbox (Flexible Box Layout)** is a one-dimensional CSS layout model. It distributes space along a single axis (horizontal or vertical) and gives you powerful alignment and distribution control — in one or two lines of CSS.\n\n> **Reality Check:** Flexbox is used in virtually every modern web interface. Navbars, card grids, form rows, button groups, footers, sidebars — all of these are trivially built with Flexbox. At Swiggy, Ola, HDFC — every UI team uses Flexbox daily. It is not optional.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this lesson you will be able to:\n- Enable Flexbox and understand the flex container and flex items\n- Control main axis alignment with `justify-content`\n- Control cross axis alignment with `align-items`\n- Use `flex-direction`, `flex-wrap`, and `gap`\n- Control item growth, shrinkage, and basis with `flex`\n- Build a navbar, card grid, sidebar layout, and centered content\n- Debug Flexbox layouts using browser DevTools\n- Explain when to use Flexbox vs Grid\n\n---\n\n## 3. Concept Explanation\n\n### Beginner Level — Enabling Flexbox\n\n```css\n/* Before Flexbox */\n.container div {\n  float: left;    /* Old way — hacky */\n  margin: 5px;\n}\n.container::after { content: ""; display: block; clear: both; } /* Clearfix! */\n\n/* With Flexbox — single line! */\n.container {\n  display: flex;  /* Magic! Children become flex items */\n}\n```\n\nWhen you apply `display: flex` to a container:\n- The container is called the **flex container**\n- All direct children become **flex items**\n- Items arrange in a row by default (left to right)\n\n### Intermediate Level — Axes\n\nFlexbox works along TWO axes:\n- **Main axis**: Direction items flow (set by `flex-direction`)\n- **Cross axis**: Perpendicular to main axis\n\n```\nflex-direction: row (default)\n\n  main axis →\n  ┌─────────────────────────────────┐\n  │ [item1] [item2] [item3] [item4] │  cross axis\n  └─────────────────────────────────┘        ↓\n\nflex-direction: column\n  ┌────────┐  ← main axis →\n  │ item1  │\n  │ item2  │  cross axis\n  │ item3  │       →\n  │ item4  │\n  └────────┘\n```\n\n### Advanced Level — The flex Shorthand\n\n```css\n/* flex: grow shrink basis */\n.item { flex: 1; }        /* flex: 1 1 0% — grows and shrinks equally */\n.item { flex: auto; }     /* flex: 1 1 auto — size based on content then grows */\n.item { flex: none; }     /* flex: 0 0 auto — does not grow or shrink */\n.item { flex: 2 1 200px; }/* 200px base, grows at 2x rate, shrinks normally */\n\n/* Understanding each component */\nflex-grow:   0  /* Do not grow (default) */\nflex-grow:   1  /* Take available space */\nflex-grow:   2  /* Take 2x as much space as flex-grow:1 items */\n\nflex-shrink: 0  /* Do not shrink even if not enough space */\nflex-shrink: 1  /* Shrink proportionally (default) */\n\nflex-basis:  0      /* Start from 0 (ignores content size) */\nflex-basis:  auto   /* Start from content size */\nflex-basis:  200px  /* Start from fixed size */\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Visual Learning\n\n```\njustify-content (main axis alignment)\n\nflex-start:    [A][B][C]          →  (items at start)\ncenter:        ···[A][B][C]···   →  (items centered)\nflex-end:      ··········[A][B][C]  (items at end)\nspace-between: [A]···[B]···[C]   →  (space between items)\nspace-around:  ·[A]··[B]··[C]·  →  (space around items)\nspace-evenly:  ·[A]·[B]·[C]·   →  (equal space everywhere)\n\nalign-items (cross axis alignment)\n\nstretch:    ┌──┐┌──┐┌────┐  Items fill full height\n            │  ││  ││    │\n            └──┘└──┘└────┘\n\nflex-start: ┌──┐┌──┐┌────┐  Items at top\n            │  ││  ││    │\n            │  ││  │└────┘\n            └──┘└──┘\n\ncenter:         ┌──┐\n            ┌──┐│  │┌────┐  Items vertically centered\n            └──┘│  ││    │\n                └──┘└────┘\n\nflex-end:       ┌──┐┌──┐  Items at bottom\n            ┌──┐│  ││  │\n            │  ││  ││  │┌────┐\n            └──┘└──┘└──┘└────┘\n\n\nflex property visualization\n\n.item { flex: 1 }        Container: [══════A══════][══════B══════]\n.item { flex: 2 }        Container: [════A════][════════B════════]\n.item { flex: 0 0 200px} Container: [200px A][──────remaining──]\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Syntax Reference — Complete Flexbox Properties\n\n```css\n/* ====== CONTAINER PROPERTIES ====== */\n\n.container {\n  /* Enable Flexbox */\n  display: flex;          /* Block flex container */\n  display: inline-flex;   /* Inline flex container */\n\n  /* Direction */\n  flex-direction: row;            /* → (default) */\n  flex-direction: row-reverse;    /* ← */\n  flex-direction: column;         /* ↓ */\n  flex-direction: column-reverse; /* ↑ */\n\n  /* Wrapping */\n  flex-wrap: nowrap;    /* All in one line (default) */\n  flex-wrap: wrap;      /* Wrap to next line */\n  flex-wrap: wrap-reverse; /* Wrap upward */\n\n  /* Shorthand */\n  flex-flow: row wrap;  /* flex-direction + flex-wrap */\n\n  /* Main axis alignment */\n  justify-content: flex-start;    /* ← */\n  justify-content: flex-end;      /* → */\n  justify-content: center;        /* ←→ */\n  justify-content: space-between; /* [a]...[b]...[c] */\n  justify-content: space-around;  /* .[a]..[b]..[c]. */\n  justify-content: space-evenly;  /* .[a].[b].[c]. */\n\n  /* Cross axis alignment */\n  align-items: stretch;    /* Fill container height (default) */\n  align-items: flex-start; /* Top */\n  align-items: flex-end;   /* Bottom */\n  align-items: center;     /* Middle */\n  align-items: baseline;   /* Align text baselines */\n\n  /* Multi-line cross axis */\n  align-content: flex-start;\n  align-content: center;\n  align-content: space-between;\n\n  /* Gap between items */\n  gap: 1rem;            /* Both axes */\n  gap: 1rem 2rem;       /* row-gap column-gap */\n  row-gap: 1rem;\n  column-gap: 2rem;\n}\n\n/* ====== ITEM PROPERTIES ====== */\n\n.item {\n  /* Growth/shrink/size */\n  flex-grow:   0;     /* Do not grow (default) */\n  flex-shrink: 1;     /* Shrink proportionally (default) */\n  flex-basis:  auto;  /* Size based on content (default) */\n  flex:        1;     /* Shorthand: grow shrink basis */\n\n  /* Override cross axis alignment */\n  align-self: auto;       /* Inherits align-items */\n  align-self: flex-start; /* Override for this item */\n  align-self: center;\n  align-self: flex-end;\n  align-self: stretch;\n\n  /* Visual order (does not affect DOM order!) */\n  order: 0;     /* Default: source order */\n  order: -1;    /* Moves to front */\n  order: 1;     /* Moves to back */\n\n  /* Prevent text overflow in flex items */\n  min-width: 0; /* Allows item to shrink below content size */\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Multiple Code Examples\n\n### Example 1 — Classic Navigation Bar\n```html\n<nav class="navbar">\n  <a href="/" class="logo">R-Learn</a>\n\n  <ul class="nav-links">\n    <li><a href="/courses">Courses</a></li>\n    <li><a href="/challenges">Challenges</a></li>\n    <li><a href="/leaderboard">Leaderboard</a></li>\n  </ul>\n\n  <div class="nav-actions">\n    <a href="/login" class="btn-ghost">Sign In</a>\n    <a href="/signup" class="btn-primary">Get Started</a>\n  </div>\n</nav>\n```\n\n```css\n.navbar {\n  display: flex;\n  align-items: center;\n  justify-content: space-between;  /* Logo | Links | Actions */\n  padding: 0 2rem;\n  height: 64px;\n  background: white;\n  border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;\n  position: sticky;\n  top: 0;\n  z-index: 100;\n}\n\n.nav-links {\n  display: flex;\n  align-items: center;\n  gap: 2rem;\n  list-style: none;\n  margin: 0;\n  padding: 0;\n}\n\n.nav-actions {\n  display: flex;\n  align-items: center;\n  gap: 1rem;\n}\n```\n\n### Example 2 — Responsive Card Grid\n```css\n/* Cards that wrap and distribute space equally */\n.course-grid {\n  display: flex;\n  flex-wrap: wrap;\n  gap: 1.5rem;\n}\n\n.course-card {\n  flex: 1 1 300px;     /* Grow, shrink, min-width 300px */\n  max-width: 400px;    /* Do not get too wide */\n}\n\n/* On mobile: full width cards */\n@media (max-width: 640px) {\n  .course-card {\n    flex: 1 1 100%;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Example 3 — Sidebar + Main Layout\n```css\n.layout {\n  display: flex;\n  min-height: 100vh;\n}\n\n.sidebar {\n  flex: 0 0 260px;    /* Fixed width, do not grow or shrink */\n  background: #1e293b;\n  padding: 2rem 1rem;\n}\n\n.main-content {\n  flex: 1;            /* Take all remaining space */\n  padding: 2rem;\n  min-width: 0;       /* Allow content to shrink */\n  overflow: auto;\n}\n\n/* Collapse sidebar on mobile */\n@media (max-width: 768px) {\n  .layout {\n    flex-direction: column;\n  }\n  .sidebar {\n    flex: none;\n    width: 100%;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Example 4 — Perfect Centering (Vertically & Horizontally)\n```css\n/* The one-liner every developer needs */\n.center-everything {\n  display: flex;\n  align-items: center;      /* Vertical center */\n  justify-content: center;  /* Horizontal center */\n\n  /* Usually needs a height */\n  min-height: 100vh;\n}\n\n/* Centering in a button */\n.btn {\n  display: inline-flex;\n  align-items: center;\n  gap: 0.5rem;  /* Space between icon and text */\n}\n\n/* Centering a modal overlay */\n.modal-overlay {\n  position: fixed;\n  inset: 0;\n  display: flex;\n  align-items: center;\n  justify-content: center;\n  background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);\n}\n```\n\n### Example 5 — Stats Row (Used in dashboards)\n```html\n<div class="stats-row">\n  <div class="stat-card">...</div>\n  <div class="stat-card">...</div>\n  <div class="stat-card">...</div>\n  <div class="stat-card">...</div>\n</div>\n```\n\n```css\n.stats-row {\n  display: flex;\n  gap: 1.5rem;\n}\n\n.stat-card {\n  flex: 1;             /* Each takes equal share */\n  background: white;\n  border-radius: 12px;\n  padding: 1.5rem;\n  border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;\n}\n\n/* Stacks on mobile */\n@media (max-width: 768px) {\n  .stats-row {\n    flex-direction: column;\n  }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Try It Yourself\n\n### Exercise 1 — Center a Card\n```\nTask: Using ONLY Flexbox (no position:absolute), center a 400x300 card\nin the middle of the viewport (vertically and horizontally).\n\nHTML:\n<div class="page">\n  <div class="card">Centered Card</div>\n</div>\n\nCSS:\n.page { /* Your flexbox code */ }\n.card { width: 400px; height: 300px; background: white; border-radius: 12px; }\n```\n\n### Exercise 2 — Build a Navbar\n```\nTask: Build a navbar with:\n- Logo on the left\n- Navigation links in the center  \n- Sign In and Sign Up buttons on the right\n- All items vertically centered\n- 64px height\nUse only flexbox for layout.\n```\n\n### Exercise 3 — Holy Grail Layout\n```\nTask: Build the classic "Holy Grail" layout:\n- Fixed header (64px)\n- Footer at bottom\n- Three-column middle: sidebar (200px) | main | sidebar (200px)\n- Main takes all remaining space\n- Full viewport height\nUse flex on body and on the middle section.\n```\n\n### Exercise 4 — Flex Calculator\n```javascript\n// Build a visual tool that shows the effect of flex properties:\n// - Add/remove flex items\n// - Change justify-content value with a dropdown\n// - Change align-items value with a dropdown\n// - Show the live result\n// - Display the CSS being applied\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Common Mistakes\n\n### Mistake 1 — flex:1 without min-width:0\n```css\n/* WRONG — long text in a flex item breaks layout */\n.item {\n  flex: 1;\n  /* Without min-width: 0, the item can overflow */\n}\n\n/* CORRECT — allow item to shrink below content size */\n.item {\n  flex: 1;\n  min-width: 0;         /* Critical for text overflow */\n  overflow: hidden;\n  text-overflow: ellipsis;\n  white-space: nowrap;\n}\n```\n\n### Mistake 2 — Using margin:auto instead of gap\n```css\n/* OLD WAY — fragile, hard to maintain */\n.item + .item {\n  margin-left: 1rem;\n}\n\n/* MODERN WAY — clean and consistent */\n.container {\n  display: flex;\n  gap: 1rem;  /* Works for all items, no selector tricks needed */\n}\n```\n\n### Mistake 3 — Forgetting flex creates inline children\n```css\n/* WRONG assumption -- flex does NOT make all children block */\n.container {\n  display: flex;\n}\n\n.item {\n  /* You can still use width, height on flex items */\n  width: 200px;      /* Works -- flex items respect width */\n  height: 100px;     /* Works */\n}\n```\n\n### Mistake 4 — order vs DOM order\n```css\n/* order changes VISUAL order, not DOM order! */\n/* Screen readers and keyboard nav still follow DOM order */\n.first-visually {\n  order: -1;  /* Appears first visually */\n              /* But DOM position is unchanged — accessibility issue! */\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. Best Practices\n\n1. **Use `gap` instead of margins** between flex items — cleaner, no edge-case issues\n2. **Use `flex: 1`** for items that should share space equally\n3. **Add `min-width: 0`** to flex items that contain overflow text\n4. **Prefer Flexbox for 1D layouts** — row of cards, nav items, a form row\n5. **Use Grid for 2D layouts** — a whole page with header/sidebar/main/footer\n6. **Use `align-self` to override** one item''s alignment without affecting others\n7. **Use `flex-direction: column`** to turn a sidebar into a vertical navigation\n\n---\n\n## 10. Real-World Usage\n\n### At Production Companies\n\n**LinkedIn Feed:** Each post card uses `display: flex` for the author info row (avatar + name + time on one line).\n\n**GitHub:** The repository header uses `justify-content: space-between` to put the repo name on the left and the star/fork buttons on the right.\n\n**Zomato:** The restaurant card uses flex for the image + details side-by-side layout, and nested flex for the rating/distance/cuisine row.\n\n**Google Search Results:** Each result uses flex for the title, URL, and snippet layout.\n\n---\n\n## 11. Interview Preparation\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `justify-content` and `align-items`?**\n> `justify-content` controls alignment along the main axis (horizontal in row, vertical in column). `align-items` controls alignment along the cross axis (vertical in row, horizontal in column). Together they control placement in 2D space.\n\n**Q: What does `flex: 1` actually mean?**\n> It is shorthand for `flex: 1 1 0%`, meaning: grow with factor 1, shrink with factor 1, starting from 0 (ignoring content size). Items with `flex: 1` share available space equally.\n\n**Q: When would you use Flexbox vs CSS Grid?**\n> Flexbox: single-axis layouts (a row of items, a vertical list, a navbar). Grid: two-dimensional layouts where you need control over both rows AND columns simultaneously (full page layout, photo grid, dashboard).\n\n**Q: How do you vertically center content in a div using Flexbox?**\n> Set `display: flex; align-items: center;` on the container. Also set a height on the container (otherwise there is no space to center within).\n\n---\n\n## 12. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What property enables Flexbox on a container?\n2. What is the main axis and how does `flex-direction` affect it?\n3. What is the difference between `justify-content` and `align-items`?\n4. How do you make items wrap to the next line?\n5. What does `flex: 1` mean?\n6. How do you prevent a flex item from growing?\n7. What is `align-self` used for?\n8. What does the `gap` property do in a flex container?\n9. How do you make two items in a flex container, with one on each side?\n10. What is `min-width: 0` used for in a flex item?\n\n---\n\n## 13. Coding Challenges\n\n### Easy — Center a Box\n```\nProblem: Using only Flexbox, center a 200x200px blue box\nin the exact middle of the screen (viewport).\n\nRequirements:\n- No position: absolute\n- No margin: auto\n- Works at any screen size\n```\n\n### Medium — Responsive Card Layout\n```\nProblem: Create a card grid using Flexbox where:\n- Desktop (>768px): 3 cards per row\n- Tablet (>480px): 2 cards per row\n- Mobile: 1 card per row\n- Cards have equal height (tallest card sets the row height)\n- 24px gap between cards\n- No JavaScript, no Grid (Flexbox only)\n```\n\n### Hard — Flex Masonry Layout\n```\nProblem: Create a masonry-style layout (Pinterest-like)\nusing only Flexbox where:\n- Items have varying heights\n- Items fill columns from top to bottom\n- 4 columns on desktop, 2 on tablet, 1 on mobile\n- No fixed heights\n\nHint: flex-direction: column + flex-wrap: wrap\n      Set a fixed height on the container\n      Items fill column by column\n```\n\n---\n\n## 14. Mini Project — Admin Dashboard Layout\n\nBuild a complete admin dashboard layout using only HTML + CSS Flexbox:\n\n```html\n<!DOCTYPE html>\n<html lang="en">\n<head>\n  <meta charset="UTF-8">\n  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">\n  <title>R-Learn Dashboard</title>\n  <style>\n    /* Reset */\n    *, *::before, *::after { box-sizing: border-box; margin: 0; padding: 0; }\n\n    body { font-family: Inter, sans-serif; background: #f8fafc; min-height: 100vh; }\n\n    /* App Shell */\n    .app-shell { display: flex; min-height: 100vh; }\n\n    /* Sidebar */\n    .sidebar {\n      flex: 0 0 240px;\n      background: #1e293b;\n      color: white;\n      display: flex;\n      flex-direction: column;\n      padding: 1.5rem 1rem;\n    }\n    .sidebar-logo { font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: bold; color: #38bdf8; margin-bottom: 2rem; }\n    .sidebar-nav  { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 0.25rem; }\n    .sidebar-link {\n      display: flex;\n      align-items: center;\n      gap: 0.75rem;\n      padding: 0.75rem 1rem;\n      border-radius: 8px;\n      color: #94a3b8;\n      text-decoration: none;\n    }\n    .sidebar-link:hover, .sidebar-link.active {\n      background: #334155;\n      color: white;\n    }\n    .sidebar-footer { margin-top: auto; }\n\n    /* Main content area */\n    .main { flex: 1; display: flex; flex-direction: column; min-width: 0; }\n\n    /* Topbar */\n    .topbar {\n      height: 64px;\n      background: white;\n      border-bottom: 1px solid #e2e8f0;\n      display: flex;\n      align-items: center;\n      justify-content: space-between;\n      padding: 0 2rem;\n    }\n    .topbar-title   { font-weight: 600; color: #0f172a; }\n    .topbar-actions { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 1rem; }\n    .avatar {\n      width: 36px; height: 36px;\n      border-radius: 50%;\n      background: #3b82f6;\n      display: flex;\n      align-items: center;\n      justify-content: center;\n      color: white;\n      font-weight: bold;\n      font-size: 0.875rem;\n    }\n\n    /* Page content */\n    .page { padding: 2rem; }\n    .page-title { font-size: 1.5rem; font-weight: bold; color: #0f172a; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }\n\n    /* Stats grid */\n    .stats-row { display: flex; gap: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 2rem; }\n    .stat-card {\n      flex: 1;\n      background: white;\n      border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;\n      border-radius: 12px;\n      padding: 1.5rem;\n    }\n    .stat-label { font-size: 0.875rem; color: #64748b; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }\n    .stat-value { font-size: 2rem; font-weight: bold; color: #0f172a; }\n    .stat-change { font-size: 0.875rem; color: #10b981; margin-top: 0.25rem; }\n\n    /* Content row */\n    .content-row { display: flex; gap: 1.5rem; }\n    .content-main { flex: 2; min-width: 0; }\n    .content-aside { flex: 1; min-width: 0; }\n    .content-card {\n      background: white;\n      border: 1px solid #e2e8f0;\n      border-radius: 12px;\n      padding: 1.5rem;\n    }\n\n    @media (max-width: 768px) {\n      .app-shell { flex-direction: column; }\n      .sidebar { flex: none; flex-direction: row; overflow-x: auto; }\n      .stats-row, .content-row { flex-direction: column; }\n    }\n  </style>\n</head>\n<body>\n  <div class="app-shell">\n    <aside class="sidebar">\n      <div class="sidebar-logo">R-Learn</div>\n      <nav class="sidebar-nav">\n        <a href="#" class="sidebar-link active">Dashboard</a>\n        <a href="#" class="sidebar-link">Courses</a>\n        <a href="#" class="sidebar-link">Challenges</a>\n        <a href="#" class="sidebar-link">Leaderboard</a>\n        <a href="#" class="sidebar-link">Analytics</a>\n      </nav>\n      <div class="sidebar-footer">\n        <a href="#" class="sidebar-link">Settings</a>\n      </div>\n    </aside>\n\n    <div class="main">\n      <header class="topbar">\n        <span class="topbar-title">Dashboard</span>\n        <div class="topbar-actions">\n          <span>Alice Sharma</span>\n          <div class="avatar">AS</div>\n        </div>\n      </header>\n\n      <div class="page">\n        <h1 class="page-title">Welcome back, Alice!</h1>\n\n        <div class="stats-row">\n          <div class="stat-card">\n            <div class="stat-label">Total XP</div>\n            <div class="stat-value">4,850</div>\n            <div class="stat-change">↑ 150 this week</div>\n          </div>\n          <div class="stat-card">\n            <div class="stat-label">Courses Enrolled</div>\n            <div class="stat-value">7</div>\n            <div class="stat-change">↑ 2 this month</div>\n          </div>\n          <div class="stat-card">\n            <div class="stat-label">Lessons Completed</div>\n            <div class="stat-value">43</div>\n            <div class="stat-change">↑ 5 this week</div>\n          </div>\n          <div class="stat-card">\n            <div class="stat-label">Current Streak</div>\n            <div class="stat-value">12 days</div>\n            <div class="stat-change">Keep it up!</div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n\n        <div class="content-row">\n          <div class="content-main">\n            <div class="content-card">\n              <h2>Continue Learning</h2>\n              <p>JavaScript ES6+ — Module 9: Async Patterns</p>\n            </div>\n          </div>\n          <div class="content-aside">\n            <div class="content-card">\n              <h2>Leaderboard</h2>\n              <p>You are #3 in your department!</p>\n            </div>\n          </div>\n        </div>\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</body>\n</html>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 15. Lesson Summary\n\n| Property | Controls | Common Values |\n|----------|----------|---------------|\n| `display: flex` | Enables Flexbox | flex, inline-flex |\n| `flex-direction` | Main axis direction | row (→), column (↓) |\n| `flex-wrap` | Single/multi-line | nowrap, wrap |\n| `justify-content` | Main axis alignment | flex-start, center, space-between |\n| `align-items` | Cross axis alignment | stretch, center, flex-start |\n| `gap` | Space between items | 1rem, 1rem 2rem |\n| `flex` | Item sizing | 1, 0 0 200px, auto |\n| `align-self` | Override align-items | center, flex-end, stretch |\n| `order` | Visual order | -1, 0, 1 |\n\nFlexbox eliminated years of CSS hacks. Once you understand axes, alignment, and the flex property, you can build any 1D layout in minutes. Practice until writing `display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between` is muscle memory.', 30, 1)
WHERE id = 'l20501';

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# useState Hook — Managing State in React\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nImagine a webpage where clicking a button changes the counter, or typing in a box updates the text, or adding an item extends a list — all without reloading. This is **state** at work, and `useState` is React''s way of managing it.\n\n`useState` is the most fundamental React hook. It allows functional components to remember and update data. Without state, React components would be static, unchangeable templates. With state, they become interactive, dynamic applications.\n\n> **Industry Reality:** Every interactive React component uses useState. Counter buttons, search boxes, toggles, forms, shopping carts, modals, tab panels — all use useState. At companies like Swiggy, Paytm, Groww — React components with useState power the core user experience.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Learning Objectives\n\nBy the end of this lesson you will be able to:\n- Declare and update state using `useState`\n- Explain how state updates trigger re-renders\n- Use the functional updater form correctly\n- Manage state for booleans, numbers, strings, objects, and arrays\n- Avoid common state mutation bugs\n- Implement controlled form inputs\n- Lift state up to share between components\n- Understand when NOT to use state\n\n---\n\n## 3. Concept Explanation\n\n### Beginner Level — What is State?\n\n```\nA Component WITHOUT state:         A Component WITH state:\n\n  [Counter]                           [Counter]\n  Count: 0  ← fixed                  Count: 5  ← can change\n  [+] button  ← does nothing         [+] button  ← updates count\n\nState = data that can change over time, causing the component to re-render.\n```\n\n### How useState Works\n```jsx\nimport { useState } from "react";\n\nfunction Counter() {\n  // 1. Declare state\n  const [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n  //     │       │              │\n  //     │       │              └─ Initial value\n  //     │       └─ Setter function (call this to update)\n  //     └─ Current state value\n\n  // 2. Use state in JSX\n  return (\n    <div>\n      <p>Count: {count}</p>  {/* Re-renders when count changes */}\n      <button onClick={() => setCount(count + 1)}>+</button>\n      <button onClick={() => setCount(count - 1)}>-</button>\n      <button onClick={() => setCount(0)}>Reset</button>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Intermediate Level — The Re-Render Cycle\n\n```\n1. Component mounts: useState(0) → count = 0, renders <p>Count: 0</p>\n\n2. User clicks [+]:\n   setCount(count + 1) = setCount(1)\n\n3. React schedules re-render\n\n4. Component function runs AGAIN:\n   useState(0) → count = 1 (React remembers the new state)\n   Renders <p>Count: 1</p>\n\n5. React compares old and new virtual DOM (diffing)\n   Updates only the changed <p> element in the real DOM\n```\n\n### Advanced Level — Functional Updates and Batching\n\n```jsx\n// PROBLEM: Stale state in async/event handlers\nconst [count, setCount] = useState(0);\n\nfunction buggyTripleIncrement() {\n  setCount(count + 1); // count is still 0!\n  setCount(count + 1); // count is still 0!\n  setCount(count + 1); // count is still 0!\n  // Result: count becomes 1 (not 3)\n}\n\n// SOLUTION: Functional updater (gets latest state)\nfunction correctTripleIncrement() {\n  setCount(prev => prev + 1);  // prev = 0, result = 1\n  setCount(prev => prev + 1);  // prev = 1, result = 2\n  setCount(prev => prev + 1);  // prev = 2, result = 3\n  // Result: count becomes 3 ✅\n}\n\n// WHEN to use functional updater:\n// - When new state depends on previous state\n// - In callbacks (event handlers, timeouts, intervals)\n// - Whenever you call setX multiple times in sequence\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Visual Learning\n\n```\nSTATE UPDATE CYCLE\n\n         useState(initialValue)\n                  │\n             First render\n          count = initialValue\n                  │\n            Render JSX\n                  │\n         User interacts\n         setCount(newValue)\n                  │\n         React schedules\n           re-render\n                  │\n         Component runs again\n         count = newValue\n                  │\n         Render new JSX\n                  │\n         React diffs old vs new\n                  │\n         Updates real DOM\n           (minimal changes)\n                  │\n              User sees update\n\n\nSTATE FLOW (Multiple components)\n\n   ❌ WRONG: Child trying to share state\n   Parent              Child A           Child B\n   │                   │                 │\n   │   let count = 0   │                 │\n   │                   │ count = 0        │ count = 0\n   │                   │ (separate!)      │ (separate!)\n\n   ✅ CORRECT: Lift state to common ancestor\n   Parent  ←── count = 5 ──┐\n   │           setCount     │\n   ├─── passes count ─────> Child A (displays count)\n   └─── passes setCount ──> Child B (can update count)\n\n\nSTATE TYPES AND PATTERNS\n\nPrimitive state:   const [name, setName] = useState("");\nBoolean toggle:    const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false);\nObject state:      const [user, setUser] = useState({ name: "", email: "" });\nArray state:       const [items, setItems] = useState([]);\nNullable:          const [user, setUser] = useState<User | null>(null);\nLazy init:         const [data, setData] = useState(() => JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem("data") || "null"));\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Syntax Reference\n\n```jsx\nimport { useState } from "react";\n\n// ═══════════════════════════════════\n// DECLARATION PATTERNS\n// ═══════════════════════════════════\n\n// Primitive\nconst [count,   setCount]   = useState(0);\nconst [name,    setName]    = useState("");\nconst [isOpen,  setIsOpen]  = useState(false);\n\n// Object\nconst [user, setUser] = useState({ name: "", email: "", xp: 0 });\n\n// Array\nconst [items, setItems] = useState([]);\n\n// Null (data not yet loaded)\nconst [user,   setUser]   = useState(null);\n\n// Lazy initialization (runs function only once, not every render)\nconst [theme, setTheme] = useState(() => {\n  return localStorage.getItem("theme") || "light";\n});\n\n// ═══════════════════════════════════\n// UPDATE PATTERNS\n// ═══════════════════════════════════\n\n// Direct\nsetCount(5);\nsetName("Alice");\nsetIsOpen(true);\n\n// Based on previous value (ALWAYS use this for state that depends on itself)\nsetCount(prev => prev + 1);\nsetIsOpen(prev => !prev);\n\n// Object (spread to preserve other fields)\nsetUser(prev => ({ ...prev, name: "Bob" }));\nsetUser(prev => ({ ...prev, xp: prev.xp + 50 }));\n\n// Array — add\nsetItems(prev => [...prev, newItem]);\n\n// Array — remove\nsetItems(prev => prev.filter(item => item.id !== targetId));\n\n// Array — update one item\nsetItems(prev => prev.map(item =>\n  item.id === targetId ? { ...item, completed: true } : item\n));\n\n// Array — sort (always create new array first)\nsetItems(prev => [...prev].sort((a, b) => a.name.localeCompare(b.name)));\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Multiple Code Examples\n\n### Example 1 — Toggle (Dark Mode, Menu, Modal)\n```jsx\nfunction App() {\n  const [isDark, setIsDark] = useState(false);\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    document.documentElement.classList.toggle("dark", isDark);\n    localStorage.setItem("theme", isDark ? "dark" : "light");\n  }, [isDark]);\n\n  return (\n    <div className={isDark ? "app dark" : "app"}>\n      <button\n        onClick={() => setIsDark(prev => !prev)}\n        aria-label={`Switch to ${isDark ? "light" : "dark"} mode`}\n      >\n        {isDark ? "🌞 Light Mode" : "🌙 Dark Mode"}\n      </button>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Example 2 — Object State (User Profile Form)\n```jsx\nfunction ProfileForm({ onSave }) {\n  const [form, setForm] = useState({\n    name:       "",\n    email:      "",\n    department: "Engineering",\n    bio:        "",\n  });\n\n  const [errors, setErrors] = useState({});\n\n  // Single handler for all fields\n  const handleChange = (e) => {\n    const { name, value } = e.target;\n    setForm(prev => ({ ...prev, [name]: value }));\n    // Clear error when user types\n    setErrors(prev => ({ ...prev, [name]: "" }));\n  };\n\n  const validate = () => {\n    const newErrors = {};\n    if (!form.name.trim())    newErrors.name  = "Name is required";\n    if (!form.email.includes("@")) newErrors.email = "Valid email required";\n    return newErrors;\n  };\n\n  const handleSubmit = (e) => {\n    e.preventDefault();\n    const validationErrors = validate();\n    if (Object.keys(validationErrors).length > 0) {\n      setErrors(validationErrors);\n      return;\n    }\n    onSave(form);\n  };\n\n  return (\n    <form onSubmit={handleSubmit}>\n      <div>\n        <label htmlFor="name">Full Name</label>\n        <input\n          id="name"\n          name="name"\n          value={form.name}\n          onChange={handleChange}\n        />\n        {errors.name && <span className="error">{errors.name}</span>}\n      </div>\n\n      <div>\n        <label htmlFor="email">Email</label>\n        <input\n          id="email"\n          name="email"\n          type="email"\n          value={form.email}\n          onChange={handleChange}\n        />\n        {errors.email && <span className="error">{errors.email}</span>}\n      </div>\n\n      <button type="submit">Save Profile</button>\n    </form>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Example 3 — Array State (Todo List)\n```jsx\nfunction TodoList() {\n  const [todos, setTodos] = useState([\n    { id: 1, text: "Complete HTML module", done: false },\n    { id: 2, text: "Build portfolio project", done: false },\n  ]);\n  const [input, setInput] = useState("");\n\n  const addTodo = () => {\n    if (!input.trim()) return;\n    setTodos(prev => [\n      ...prev,\n      { id: Date.now(), text: input.trim(), done: false }\n    ]);\n    setInput(""); // Reset input\n  };\n\n  const toggleTodo = (id) => {\n    setTodos(prev =>\n      prev.map(todo =>\n        todo.id === id ? { ...todo, done: !todo.done } : todo\n      )\n    );\n  };\n\n  const deleteTodo = (id) => {\n    setTodos(prev => prev.filter(todo => todo.id !== id));\n  };\n\n  const remaining = todos.filter(t => !t.done).length;\n\n  return (\n    <div className="todo-app">\n      <h1>Todos ({remaining} remaining)</h1>\n\n      <div className="add-row">\n        <input\n          value={input}\n          onChange={e => setInput(e.target.value)}\n          onKeyDown={e => e.key === "Enter" && addTodo()}\n          placeholder="Add a new task..."\n        />\n        <button onClick={addTodo}>Add</button>\n      </div>\n\n      <ul>\n        {todos.map(todo => (\n          <li key={todo.id} className={todo.done ? "done" : ""}>\n            <input\n              type="checkbox"\n              checked={todo.done}\n              onChange={() => toggleTodo(todo.id)}\n            />\n            <span>{todo.text}</span>\n            <button onClick={() => deleteTodo(todo.id)}>✕</button>\n          </li>\n        ))}\n      </ul>\n\n      {todos.some(t => t.done) && (\n        <button onClick={() => setTodos(prev => prev.filter(t => !t.done))}>\n          Clear Completed\n        </button>\n      )}\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n### Example 4 — Multi-step Form\n```jsx\nfunction MultiStepSignup() {\n  const [step, setStep]     = useState(1);\n  const [formData, setFormData] = useState({\n    name:       "",\n    email:      "",\n    password:   "",\n    department: "",\n    role:       "",\n  });\n\n  const updateField = (field, value) =>\n    setFormData(prev => ({ ...prev, [field]: value }));\n\n  const steps = [\n    {\n      title: "Personal Info",\n      content: (\n        <>\n          <input\n            placeholder="Full Name"\n            value={formData.name}\n            onChange={e => updateField("name", e.target.value)}\n          />\n          <input\n            placeholder="Email"\n            type="email"\n            value={formData.email}\n            onChange={e => updateField("email", e.target.value)}\n          />\n        </>\n      ),\n    },\n    {\n      title: "Security",\n      content: (\n        <input\n          placeholder="Password"\n          type="password"\n          value={formData.password}\n          onChange={e => updateField("password", e.target.value)}\n        />\n      ),\n    },\n    {\n      title: "Work Details",\n      content: (\n        <select\n          value={formData.department}\n          onChange={e => updateField("department", e.target.value)}\n        >\n          <option value="">Select Department</option>\n          <option value="engineering">Engineering</option>\n          <option value="design">Design</option>\n          <option value="marketing">Marketing</option>\n        </select>\n      ),\n    },\n  ];\n\n  return (\n    <div>\n      {/* Progress indicator */}\n      <div className="steps">\n        {steps.map((s, i) => (\n          <div key={i} className={i + 1 === step ? "active" : i + 1 < step ? "done" : ""}>\n            {i + 1}. {s.title}\n          </div>\n        ))}\n      </div>\n\n      <h2>{steps[step - 1].title}</h2>\n      <div>{steps[step - 1].content}</div>\n\n      <div className="actions">\n        {step > 1 && <button onClick={() => setStep(s => s - 1)}>Back</button>}\n        {step < steps.length\n          ? <button onClick={() => setStep(s => s + 1)}>Next</button>\n          : <button onClick={() => console.log("Submit:", formData)}>Submit</button>\n        }\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Try It Yourself\n\n### Exercise 1 — Click Counter\n```\nBuild a counter component that:\n- Shows current count\n- Has + and - buttons\n- Has a Reset button\n- Does not allow count below 0\n- Shows a message "Maximum reached!" when count hits 10\n- Changes background color based on count (green < 5, yellow 5-8, red > 8)\n```\n\n### Exercise 2 — Character Counter\n```\nBuild a text area with character counter:\n- Shows characters typed / max (like Twitter)\n- Remaining characters countdown\n- Text turns red when over limit\n- Disable submit when over limit\n```\n\n### Exercise 3 — Shopping Cart\n```\nBuild a product list with shopping cart:\n- 5 static products with name, price, image\n- Add to Cart button (shows quantity if already added)\n- Cart icon in header showing total items\n- Cart sidebar/drawer showing items with quantity controls\n- Remove item functionality\n- Total price calculation\n- Checkout button (just console.log the cart)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Common Mistakes\n\n### Mistake 1 — Mutating state directly\n```jsx\n// WRONG — mutation does NOT trigger re-render\nconst [user, setUser] = useState({ name: "Alice" });\nuser.name = "Bob";    // Direct mutation!\nsetUser(user);         // React thinks nothing changed (same reference)\n\n// CORRECT — create new object\nsetUser(prev => ({ ...prev, name: "Bob" }));\nsetUser({ ...user, name: "Bob" });\n```\n\n### Mistake 2 — Mutating arrays directly\n```jsx\n// WRONG — these all mutate the original array\nconst [items, setItems] = useState([1, 2, 3]);\nitems.push(4);       // ❌ Mutates\nitems.pop();         // ❌ Mutates\nitems.splice(0, 1);  // ❌ Mutates\nsetItems(items);     // React sees same reference, no re-render!\n\n// CORRECT — always create new array\nsetItems([...items, 4]);              // Add\nsetItems(items.slice(0, -1));         // Remove last\nsetItems(items.filter(i => i !== 1)); // Remove specific\nsetItems([...items].sort());          // Sort (spread then sort)\n```\n\n### Mistake 3 — Using state for derived values\n```jsx\n// WRONG — redundant state that could be computed\nconst [items, setItems]         = useState([]);\nconst [itemCount, setItemCount] = useState(0);\n\nfunction addItem(item) {\n  setItems(prev => [...prev, item]);\n  setItemCount(prev => prev + 1);  // Redundant! Out of sync risk!\n}\n\n// CORRECT — derive from existing state\nconst [items, setItems] = useState([]);\nconst itemCount = items.length;  // Computed, always in sync\n```\n\n### Mistake 4 — Not using functional update form\n```jsx\n// WRONG in async contexts or when calling setState multiple times\nconst incrementThrice = () => {\n  setCount(count + 1);  // Stale closure! count is still 0 for all three\n  setCount(count + 1);\n  setCount(count + 1);\n  // Result: count = 1 (not 3)\n};\n\n// CORRECT\nconst incrementThrice = () => {\n  setCount(prev => prev + 1);  // prev = 0, result = 1\n  setCount(prev => prev + 1);  // prev = 1, result = 2\n  setCount(prev => prev + 1);  // prev = 2, result = 3\n  // Result: count = 3 ✅\n};\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. Best Practices\n\n1. **Never mutate state directly** — always create new objects/arrays\n2. **Use functional updates** when new state depends on old state\n3. **Keep state minimal** — derive what you can (count = items.length, not stored separately)\n4. **Lift state up** when two components need to share the same state\n5. **Use single change handler** for form objects (handleChange with computed property names)\n6. **Lazy initialization** for expensive initial state computation\n7. **Do not store what you can compute** — computed values belong outside useState\n\n---\n\n## 10. Real-World Usage\n\n### At Indian Tech Companies\n\n**Groww (Trading App)**\n```jsx\n// Stock price display with real-time state\nconst [price, setPrice]   = useState(initialPrice);\nconst [change, setChange] = useState(0);\nconst [trend, setTrend]   = useState("neutral"); // up/down/neutral\n\nuseEffect(() => {\n  const ws = new WebSocket(`wss://api.groww.in/stock/${symbol}`);\n  ws.onmessage = (e) => {\n    const data = JSON.parse(e.data);\n    setChange(data.price - price);\n    setTrend(data.price > price ? "up" : "down");\n    setPrice(data.price);\n  };\n  return () => ws.close();\n}, [symbol]);\n```\n\n---\n\n## 11. Interview Preparation\n\n**Q: What is the difference between state and props?**\n> Props are inputs passed FROM a parent — read-only in the component receiving them. State is data OWNED and managed by the component — it can change over time causing re-renders. Props flow down; state stays local (until lifted).\n\n**Q: Why should you never mutate state directly?**\n> React uses reference equality to detect state changes. If you mutate an object and pass the same reference to setState, React sees the same reference and does NOT re-render. Always create new objects/arrays so React detects the change.\n\n**Q: What is the functional update form of setState and when do you use it?**\n> `setCount(prev => prev + 1)`. Use it when new state depends on old state, especially in event handlers or when calling setState multiple times in a row. It guarantees you get the latest state, not a stale closure value.\n\n**Q: What triggers a re-render in React?**\n> (1) setState is called with a different value, (2) parent component re-renders and passes new props, (3) context value changes. Re-renders are how React keeps the UI in sync with state.\n\n**Q: How do you update a nested object in state?**\n> Use spread at each level:\n> ```javascript\n> setUser(prev => ({ ...prev, address: { ...prev.address, city: "Mumbai" } }));\n> ```\n> Or consider using useReducer or Immer for deeply nested state.\n\n---\n\n## 12. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What does `useState` return?\n2. What happens after you call a setState function?\n3. How do you correctly add an item to an array in state?\n4. When should you use the functional update form `setState(prev => ...)`?\n5. What is the difference between `state` and `props`?\n6. How do you update one property of an object in state without losing other properties?\n7. Can you store a function in state? What is the difference between `useState(fn)` and `useState(() => fn())`?\n8. How do you share state between two sibling components?\n9. What does "lifting state up" mean?\n10. Name three things you should NOT store in state.\n\n---\n\n## 13. Coding Challenges\n\n### Easy — Counter with Min/Max\n```\nBuild a counter that:\n- Starts at 0\n- Min: 0 (disable - button at 0)\n- Max: 10 (disable + button at 10)\n- Reset button always available\n- Display shows "LOW", "MEDIUM", or "HIGH" based on value\n```\n\n### Medium — Multi-Select Tag Input\n```\nBuild a tag input component:\n- Text input where pressing Enter adds a tag\n- Each tag shown as a pill with × to remove\n- No duplicate tags allowed\n- Max 5 tags (show count: "3/5 tags")\n- Clear all button\n- Output: array of current tags\n\nExample state: [\"React\", \"TypeScript\", \"Node.js\"]\n```\n\n### Hard — Shopping Cart with Quantity\n```\nBuild a full shopping cart:\n- Product grid with 6 products\n- Each product: image, name, price, Add to Cart button\n- Cart shows item count badge on cart icon\n- Cart drawer slides in from right\n- Cart items: image, name, quantity (+ -), price × qty, remove\n- Subtotal, 18% GST, Total\n- Empty cart state\n- Checkout button\nAll state managed with useState only (no Context, no Redux)\n```\n\n---\n\n## 14. Mini Project — Kanban Board\n\nBuild a simple Kanban board (like Jira/Trello) using useState:\n\n```jsx\nconst COLUMNS = ["Todo", "In Progress", "Done"];\n\nfunction KanbanBoard() {\n  const [cards, setCards] = useState([\n    { id: 1, title: "Learn React Hooks",    column: "Todo" },\n    { id: 2, title: "Build portfolio",      column: "In Progress" },\n    { id: 3, title: "Complete HTML module", column: "Done" },\n  ]);\n  const [newTitle, setNewTitle] = useState("");\n\n  const addCard = () => {\n    if (!newTitle.trim()) return;\n    setCards(prev => [\n      ...prev,\n      { id: Date.now(), title: newTitle.trim(), column: "Todo" }\n    ]);\n    setNewTitle("");\n  };\n\n  const moveCard = (id, direction) => {\n    setCards(prev => prev.map(card => {\n      if (card.id !== id) return card;\n      const colIndex = COLUMNS.indexOf(card.column);\n      const newIndex = colIndex + direction;\n      if (newIndex < 0 || newIndex >= COLUMNS.length) return card;\n      return { ...card, column: COLUMNS[newIndex] };\n    }));\n  };\n\n  const deleteCard = (id) =>\n    setCards(prev => prev.filter(c => c.id !== id));\n\n  return (\n    <div style={{ fontFamily: "Inter, sans-serif", padding: "2rem" }}>\n      <h1>My Kanban Board</h1>\n\n      <div style={{ display: "flex", gap: "1rem", marginBottom: "1rem" }}>\n        <input\n          value={newTitle}\n          onChange={e => setNewTitle(e.target.value)}\n          onKeyDown={e => e.key === "Enter" && addCard()}\n          placeholder="New task title..."\n          style={{ flex: 1, padding: "0.5rem", borderRadius: "6px", border: "1px solid #ddd" }}\n        />\n        <button onClick={addCard}>Add Task</button>\n      </div>\n\n      <div style={{ display: "flex", gap: "1rem" }}>\n        {COLUMNS.map(col => (\n          <div key={col} style={{\n            flex: 1, background: "#f8fafc",\n            border: "1px solid #e2e8f0", borderRadius: "12px", padding: "1rem"\n          }}>\n            <h3 style={{ marginBottom: "1rem", color: "#475569" }}>\n              {col} ({cards.filter(c => c.column === col).length})\n            </h3>\n\n            {cards.filter(c => c.column === col).map(card => (\n              <div key={card.id} style={{\n                background: "white", border: "1px solid #e2e8f0",\n                borderRadius: "8px", padding: "0.75rem", marginBottom: "0.75rem"\n              }}>\n                <p style={{ margin: 0, marginBottom: "0.5rem" }}>{card.title}</p>\n                <div style={{ display: "flex", gap: "0.5rem" }}>\n                  <button onClick={() => moveCard(card.id, -1)}>←</button>\n                  <button onClick={() => moveCard(card.id, 1)}>→</button>\n                  <button onClick={() => deleteCard(card.id)} style={{ marginLeft: "auto" }}>✕</button>\n                </div>\n              </div>\n            ))}\n          </div>\n        ))}\n      </div>\n    </div>\n  );\n}\n\nexport default KanbanBoard;\n```\n\n**Extend it:**\n1. Add priority levels (Low/Medium/High) with color coding\n2. Add due date field\n3. Persist to localStorage\n4. Add card count per column\n5. Add filter by priority\n\n---\n\n## 15. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Takeaway |\n|---------|-------------|\n| useState | Hook that adds state to functional components |\n| [value, setter] | Destructured return: current value and updater function |\n| setter(newValue) | Direct update — use when state is independent |\n| setter(prev => ...) | Functional update — use when new state depends on old |\n| Never mutate | Always return new objects/arrays — React detects by reference |\n| Re-render | Called when state changes — React updates only what changed |\n| Derived state | Compute from state, do not store separately |\n| Lift state up | Move to common ancestor to share between siblings |\n| Lazy init | useState(() => fn()) for expensive initial values |\n\nuseState is the cornerstone of React. Every other hook — useEffect, useCallback, useMemo, useReducer — builds on the same model of state-driven re-rendering. Master useState and you understand React''s fundamental contract: UI = f(state).', 35, 1)
